Here's a sample PHP code that uses `php-text-analysis` for parts of speech tagging and then generates a Latex code representation:

```php
<?php

require_once 'vendor/autoload.php';

use Text_Analysis;

function tagAndFormatSentence($sentence) {
    // Initialize the POS tagger using 'php-text-analysis'
    $tagger = Text_Analysis::factory('POS', ['model' => 'en']);

    // Tokenize and tag the parts of speech
    $tokens = $tagger->tokenize($sentence);
    $tagged = $tagger->tag($tokens);

    // Prepare Latex formatted output
    $latexOutput = "\\begin{tabular}{|c|c|}\n\\hline\nWord & Part of Speech \\\\\n\\hline\n";

    foreach ($tagged as $taggedToken) {
        $word = $taggedToken->getToken();
        // Simple mapping for demonstration. In real scenarios, use actual POS tags.
        $posTag = $taggedToken->getPos();
        switch($posTag){
            case 'NN': $latexOutput .= "$word & Noun \\\\"; break;
            case 'VB': $latexOutput .= "$word & Verb \\\\"; break;
            case 'JJ': $latexOutput .= "$word & Adjective \\\\"; break;
            default: $latexOutput .= "$word & $posTag \\\\"; // Other tags
        }
        $latexOutput .= "\\hline\n";
    }

    $latexOutput .= "\\end{tabular}";

    return $latexOutput;
}

$sentence = "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.";
echo tagAndFormatSentence($sentence);

?>
```

This PHP code uses `php-text-analysis` to tag parts of speech and generates a Latex formatted table displaying each word with its identified part of speech. Keep in mind that this is a very simplified example. `php-text-analysis`'s accuracy may not be as high as more advanced libraries, and the POS tags are being naively mapped to basic categories for this Latex output. For professional-grade NLP tasks, consider more robust solutions or integrating a Python NLP library through a PHP-Python bridge. Also, ensure to install the `php-text-analysis` library via Composer before executing the code.

